On National Cancer Survivors Day, the United States honors the millions of Americans and people worldwide who have survived cancer. The article emphasizes the importance of the dedicated healthcare professionals and researchers who have contributed to improving cancer prevention and treatment. It also highlights the need to focus on pediatric cancer and increase the survival rate for children and adolescents diagnosed with the disease. The Childhood Cancer Survivorship, Treatment, Access, and Research ("STAR") Act of 2018 was signed into law last year, which aims to support pediatric cancer research and survivors. The article mentions that the President is working with Congress to invest $500 million over the next decade to further understand the causes and find better cures for childhood cancer. The article concludes by acknowledging the strength and resilience of cancer survivors and expressing support for those currently facing the disease.